11:20.800 --> 11:23.200
And you did that. It was a great show,
wasn't it, ladies and gentlemen?

11:23.300 --> 11:26.233
They didn't fool them, but we had
a great time watching you work.

11:26.300 --> 11:28.433
Ladies and gentlemen,
Joel Meyers and Spidey.

11:29.733 --> 11:31.067
Take care, guys.

11:34.133 --> 11:35.267
What's this behind my ear?

11:35.333 --> 11:37.200
Oh, it's just our next potential fooler.

11:40.900 --> 11:43.333
<i>My name is Rick Lax,</i>
<i>and I invent magic tricks.</i>

11:43.400 --> 11:46.167
When you see a magician
do a magic trick,

11:46.533 --> 11:48.000
<i>they probably didn't think of it,</i>

11:48.300 --> 11:49.333
I did.

11:49.400 --> 11:52.133
Every day, I just go to coffee
shops and think up new magic tricks.

11:52.967 --> 11:54.967
<i>I'm a little bit of a spectacle</i>
<i>because everyone else is out</i>

11:55.033 --> 11:57.300
drinking their coffee and
I'm making flowers disappear.

11:58.233 --> 12:02.267
Eight years ago, I graduated law school,
and then I passed the bar,

12:02.600 --> 12:05.833
<i>and I drove all the way to Las Vegas</i>
<i>to write a book about deception,</i>

12:05.900 --> 12:08.600
<i>and I just lost track of time,</i>
<i>and here I still am.</i>

12:08.933 --> 12:11.300
I came this close to being a lawyer.

12:11.367 --> 12:13.933
<i>I've spent so many years behind</i>
<i>the camera coming up with tricks</i>

12:14.000 --> 12:16.433
for other magicians,
and now it's my chance to go in

12:16.500 --> 12:18.067
front of the camera and see what I can do.

12:18.167 --> 12:21.267
But depending on how I do on Fool Us,
I might go back to law.

12:22.200 --> 12:24.200
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

12:27.967 --> 12:30.533
This next gentleman is a Renaissance man.

12:30.600 --> 12:33.700
I don't know if that means he paints
chapel ceilings like Michelangelo,

12:33.767 --> 12:36.000
or he's a kick-ass
Ninja turtle like Raphael.

12:36.067 --> 12:38.467
Let's find out as we meet Rick Lax.

12:38.633 --> 12:40.433
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

12:43.667 --> 12:45.867
Ladies and gentlemen,
please welcome to the stage,

12:45.933 --> 12:47.767
Misters Penn and Teller.
Come on up, guys.

12:47.833 --> 12:49.200
Come on up.

12:49.967 --> 12:52.133
Penn right here.
Teller right there.

12:54.800 --> 12:56.000
Sure.

12:56.067 --> 12:59.700
I'm about to make a shuffled
deck of playing cards

12:59.933 --> 13:03.400
magically appear inside
the breast pocket of Mr. Penn Jillette,

13:03.467 --> 13:05.267
and it's gonna happen right now.

13:05.333 --> 13:06.967
Penn, reach in there and pull them out.

13:07.533 --> 13:09.900
-I do have a deck of shuffled cards.
-I'll take them.

13:09.967 --> 13:11.533
So I assume... Thank you.

13:11.633 --> 13:13.033
(APPLAUSE)

13:14.100 --> 13:16.200
I'm gonna give the cards a quick shuffle.

13:16.267 --> 13:17.867
And as I do it, let me ask you,

13:17.933 --> 13:20.367
before you put the cards in your pocket,

13:20.467 --> 13:21.733
did you also shuffle them?

13:21.800 --> 13:23.267
-Yes, I did.
-Okay, great.

13:23.333 --> 13:27.867
Now, Teller, there's 12 cards in the deck
that I'm really good at memorizing.

13:28.167 --> 13:29.600
I'm gonna go through the cards right now.

13:29.667 --> 13:33.600
I'm gonna take out those 12,
and when I do it, oh, boy, is it boring.

13:34.033 --> 13:37.533
Could not be more boring,
so I figured while this is happening,

13:37.600 --> 13:41.867
one of us should entertain the audience
by reciting a nice, long poem.

13:43.167 --> 13:45.300
(LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE)

13:53.067 --> 13:54.900
We'll have someone else do it.

13:54.967 --> 13:57.267
Penn, is there a poem you like?

13:57.600 --> 13:58.733
Well, there's a few.

13:58.800 --> 14:01.600
I've seen the greatest minds of
my generation destroyed by madness.

14:01.667 --> 14:03.033
Do you want Howl?
Or do you want

14:03.100 --> 14:04.333
The Outlook wasn't brilliant for...

14:04.400 --> 14:05.767
The Outlook...

