What I'd like you to do is to
pull on the chain,

23:54.800 --> 23:56.233
and as you back away to each end...

23:56.300 --> 23:57.767
(LAUGHTER)

23:57.833 --> 23:59.167
As you back away to each end,

23:59.233 --> 24:02.067
feeling each link to make sure
it's completely solid.

24:04.167 --> 24:07.400
Now you'll also notice that there's
a key tag at each end of the chain.

24:07.467 --> 24:09.033
-Yeah.
-And what I'd like you to do

24:09.533 --> 24:12.133
is to write your initials, draw a picture,

24:12.333 --> 24:16.033
just mark it in a way that you'll be able
to recognize it when you see it again.

24:21.067 --> 24:22.400
(LAUGHTER)

24:28.933 --> 24:30.000
You can keep the markers.

24:30.067 --> 24:31.233
-Wow.
-I'll take the chain,

24:31.533 --> 24:33.233
and you can enjoy
the show from your seats.

24:33.433 --> 24:34.833
Thank you so much for your help.

24:35.200 --> 24:36.833
(APPLAUSE)

24:39.433 --> 24:43.233
Now what you're about to see
may seem unbelievable.

24:43.967 --> 24:48.200
Some of you may look at this as a trick
or a puzzle to be solved,

24:48.867 --> 24:51.700
but I hope more of you look
at this as inspiration

24:51.800 --> 24:54.433
in knowing that nothing is impossible.

24:55.400 --> 24:58.033
I want to give everybody one last look
at the marks from

24:58.500 --> 25:01.967
Penn and Teller.

25:03.400 --> 25:05.567
'Cause in a moment,
I'm gonna pass this chain

25:05.633 --> 25:07.600
right through the middle of my body.

25:08.667 --> 25:10.867
Now there have been times where
I've felt held back

25:10.933 --> 25:12.667
from accomplishing something in my life,

25:13.133 --> 25:18.100
and magic has always been there
to remind me that no matter what,

25:18.967 --> 25:24.000
I can always, if I use my imagination,
get through anything.

25:27.600 --> 25:28.967
(APPLAUSE)

25:35.300 --> 25:38.500
Penn, Teller, I want you to
check the tags to make sure

25:38.567 --> 25:40.167
they are the same tags,

25:40.233 --> 25:43.000
and you can keep that chain
as my gift to you.

25:43.100 --> 25:44.200
-Thank you so much.
-Thank you very much.

25:44.267 --> 25:45.633
My name is Marcus Eddie.

25:47.100 --> 25:48.833
Marcus Eddie, ladies and gentlemen.

25:49.500 --> 25:51.033
Fantastic. Wow.

25:51.167 --> 25:53.300
That was very, very impressive.

25:53.967 --> 25:55.133
You know, I noticed there seemed
to be a theme

25:55.200 --> 25:56.433
in what you were talking about.

25:56.500 --> 25:57.633
Talking about
getting through things

25:57.700 --> 25:58.733
and nothing being impossible.

25:58.833 --> 26:00.300
Is that something you hope
to spread with your magic?

26:00.367 --> 26:02.133
Is that a message you believe
in getting out there?

26:02.200 --> 26:03.500
Yes, definitely. With magic

26:03.567 --> 26:05.167
I want to inspire
everybody to let them know

26:05.233 --> 26:07.533
that you can accomplish anything
that you want to.

26:07.600 --> 26:09.800
You just gotta have the guts
to go for your dreams,

26:09.867 --> 26:10.900
so there you go.

26:10.967 --> 26:12.600
Now you weren't always doing this,
were you?

26:12.667 --> 26:13.800
-No, I wasn't.
-What were you doing?

26:13.867 --> 26:14.900
What was your job before this?

26:14.967 --> 26:16.900
Most of my jobs were, like,
customer service,

26:16.967 --> 26:19.633
cubicle jobs,
and I was just,

26:19.900 --> 26:22.300
I felt like my potential wasn't being met,

26:22.367 --> 26:24.600
so I just, I decided to take
a leap of faith,

26:24.900 --> 26:27.967
and I really wanted to show my daughter
that she can also follow her dreams,

26:28.033 --> 26:31.600
and she doesn't have to go the same path
that everybody goes through, so yeah.

26:31.667 --> 26:33.400
Wow, that's a lovely thing.
That really is.

26:33.700 --> 26:35.567
-So leading by example.
-Yes.

26:35.633 --> 26:38.733
Okay, I think they're ready
to tell you what their verdict is.

26:38.800 --> 26:40.133
Let's go to Penn. Penn,

26:40.200 --> 26:42.467
what do you think of Marcus
and do you know how it was done?

26:42.967 --> 26:45.400
Well, I gotta tell you, you know,
a lot of people come

26:45.467 --> 26:48.367
up here with stuff that they've
gotten somewhere else.

26:48.433 --> 26:53.467
Now this has a little bit of
a lineage with Harbin and with Bob Sheets,

26:53.667 --> 26:56.700
but we really do believe you invented it.

26:57.033 --> 27:00.400
This variation seems
to be very much yours.

27:00.700 --> 27:04.600
We also love the fact, you know,
Teller and I are cheap carny trash,

27:04.667 --> 27:06.233
so when you bribe us...

27:06.767 --> 27:09.467
When you bribe us with
brand-new shiny chain,

27:09.867 --> 27:14.700
and brand-new pens, we're very,
very eager to have you fool us,

27:15.100 --> 27:18.467
but I think the fact is that if
you fooled us right now,

27:18.733 --> 27:20.967
we'd want to go up there
and pat you on the back.

27:21.167 --> 27:24.100
And I don't think you really did
completely fool us,

27:24.300 --> 27:26.367
and I think you know what
I'm talking about. Is that right?

27:26.433 --> 27:27.667
That's it.
You did a great job.

27:27.733 --> 27:29.200
-Great job.
-What a great trick.

27:30.133 --> 27:32.533
It is my honor to actually
perform for you.

27:32.600 --> 27:35.033
Both of you have definitely been
an inspiration to me, so thank you.

27:35.100 --> 27:36.567
It's a wonderful trick, man.
Wonderful trick.

27:36.633 --> 27:37.933
Thank you so much.

27:38.000 --> 27:39.400
So you're...

27:39.967 --> 27:41.167
You're comfortable?

27:41.833 --> 27:43.600
-And thanks!
-Yes, yes.

27:43.667 --> 27:45.800
So, Marcus, you're comfortable
they busted you.

27:45.867 --> 27:47.067
You didn't fool them this time.

27:47.133 --> 27:48.600
-They are the masters.
-I gonna give you the chance.

27:48.667 --> 27:51.133
Do you want to get that chain and
those pens back before you go?

27:51.233 --> 27:52.633
-No, no, they're good.
-They're good?

27:52.800 --> 27:54.900
Marcus, it was great to meet you.
What a nice, young man.

27:54.967 --> 27:56.767
-Marcus Eddie, ladies and gentlemen.
-Thank you so much.

27:56.900 --> 27:58.167
Congratulations.

27:58.233 --> 27:59.600
Great job.

28:00.933 --> 28:03.133
Let's meet our next heartwarming act.

28:05.767 --> 28:08.367
I'm Bruce Gold, and I am
a comedy magician.

28:08.433 --> 28:10.167
<i>Though not always in that order.</i>

28:11.300 --> 28:13.533
What is it with kids and their
fascination with magic?

28:13.600 --> 28:15.133
When I was 14 years old,

28:15.200 --> 28:19.000
<i>the first trick I bought was called</i>
<i>"The Appearing Cane."</i>

28:19.333 --> 28:22.167
<i>When I was 15, I did a birthday</i>
<i>party for a neighbor.</i>

28:22.233 --> 28:23.233
<i>It was a 30 minute show.</i>

28:23.300 --> 28:26.633
I was paid $30,
and I did the math, $1 a minute.

28:26.700 --> 28:28.167
This is a genius profession.

28:28.433 --> 28:29.633
I'm gonna be a magician.

28:29.767 --> 28:32.067
I've always wondered about
the difference between a comedian

28:32.200 --> 28:34.700
<i>who does magic and a magician</i>
<i>who does comedy.</i>

28:35.100 --> 28:36.400
<i>And I'm not really sure which one I am,</i>

28:36.467 --> 28:38.767
<i>but I know if you're doing comedy first,</i>

28:38.833 --> 28:40.900
you better have a lot of laughs
in your show.

28:40.967 --> 28:42.667
You know what's crazy?
I'll tell you crazy.

28:42.733 --> 28:45.667
Crazy would be a network
television show where magicians

28:45.733 --> 28:46.933
tried to fool Penn and Teller.

28:47.000 --> 28:48.333
(DRUM ROLL)

28:48.833 --> 28:50.633
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

28:52.000 --> 28:55.867
This next performer is a combination
of a stand-up comic and a magician,

28:55.933 --> 28:58.100
which means his therapy bill
is twice as high.

28:58.167 --> 29:00.533
Will you please welcome Bruce Gold.

29:00.667 --> 29:01.967
Thank you.

29:02.033 --> 29:03.367
Thank you.

29:03.567 --> 29:05.200
-(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)
-Thank you very much.

29:05.267 --> 29:06.567
Thank you, wow.

29:06.633 --> 29:10.167
For this trick, I'm gonna need the help
of a lady from the audience,

29:10.233 --> 29:11.800
so I'll just look for a friendly face.

29:12.300 --> 29:14.433
Let's see, hi, you have
a very pretty smile. You help?

29:14.967 --> 29:16.400
Give her some encouragement, right?

29:18.333 --> 29:19.567
Take my hand.

29:20.033 --> 29:22.133
Follow me. I've been here before.
I know the way.

29:23.167 --> 29:25.300
Right over here to my right,
turn around, face the lovely people.

29:25.433 --> 29:26.933
-Tell me your name.
-May.

29:27.000 --> 29:28.600
Hi, May, nice to meet you.

29:28.667 --> 29:29.700
Come with me right over here.

29:29.767 --> 29:32.900
Um, are you afraid of snakes?

29:33.333 --> 29:35.200
-No.
-Good. Ooh, ah, well.

29:35.267 --> 29:36.567
(IMITATES BOW AND ARROW FIRING)
Hunger Games, ah!

29:36.633 --> 29:38.667
Snakes, bring it on.
I like your style.

29:38.733 --> 29:39.967
All right, guess what I have?

29:40.733 --> 29:42.433
-Snake.
-Snakes, plural.

29:42.500 --> 29:44.667
Live one and a dead one.
Reach in, let's see which one you get.

29:44.733 --> 29:45.967
Go ahead.

29:46.700 --> 29:48.600
Oh, suddenly we're a little less
than cooperative.

29:48.667 --> 29:50.667
All right, stay right there.
I'll protect you.

29:50.733 --> 29:53.100
Underneath this box, something
far more dangerous than a serpent.

29:53.333 --> 29:55.200
It's a toaster.

29:55.267 --> 29:57.733
-(CANNED SCREAMING)
-Wait, I can control it.

29:58.933 --> 30:00.433
Brought my own frightened crowd
with me, May.

30:00.500 --> 30:03.367
It's a toaster, or if you're a
thrill-seeker, a bath toy.

30:03.600 --> 30:05.233
-(LAUGHTER)
-Now, um...

30:05.800 --> 30:07.700
Did I not just say it was
dangerous, right? Okay.

30:08.067 --> 30:10.933
May, have you seen the game
shows on TV with the prize girls?

30:11.033 --> 30:13.033
-Yeah.
-Awesome. Okay, assume the position.

30:14.000 --> 30:15.667
Let me help, let me help.
Stand right here.

30:15.967 --> 30:17.100
Right here, right here.
Perfect.

30:17.167 --> 30:19.067
A little more forward,
left hand out like so.

30:19.267 --> 30:21.133
Good. Right hand out, palm up.
Perfect.

30:21.200 --> 30:23.067
I'm gonna have the announcer
describe the toaster

30:23.133 --> 30:25.100
and then you model it like the
prize girls on TV. Perfect.

30:25.667 --> 30:27.000
Then I'll say, "Show them the card,"

30:27.067 --> 30:28.533
and when I say that,
you'll lift this card up.

30:28.600 --> 30:31.133
It has the price on the front,
and don't forget to smile.

30:31.233 --> 30:33.533
Perfect, okay. All right.

30:33.600 --> 30:37.767
Mr. Announcer, tell the lovely
May and all of us all about it.

30:38.633 --> 30:41.900
ANNOUNCER: <i>Sure thing, Bruce.</i>
<i>Yes, it's no ordinary toaster.</i>

30:42.000 --> 30:46.433
<i>It's a Toastmaster</i>
<i>for masterful toasting slice after slice.</i>

30:47.067 --> 30:49.967
-Show the card.
<i>-Retail value, $19.95.</i>

30:50.133 --> 30:51.467
Big smile.

30:51.600 --> 30:53.000
(APPLAUSE)

30:54.800 --> 30:58.000
Wow, way to own it, May.

30:58.067 --> 30:59.600
Well done.

30:59.833 --> 31:02.267
And I have captured your moment
in this wallet-size photo.

31:02.333 --> 31:04.300
This will be yours after
the show for...

31:04.633 --> 31:06.267
(LAUGHTER)

31:06.333 --> 31:08.433
May, I don't know if you noticed
as you modeled the toaster,

31:08.500 --> 31:11.333
which you did superbly incidentally,
it's a one-slicer.

31:11.800 --> 31:14.433
Real toaster made by Toastmaster
back in the forties.

31:14.500 --> 31:17.033
But I wouldn't waste your time
with some wacky antique, May.

31:17.100 --> 31:22.067
This is not just a one-slice toaster,
it's the world's only psychic toaster.

31:22.400 --> 31:23.933
(LAUGHTER)

31:24.133 --> 31:28.067
It's an adventure into the world
of wonder and ESP.

31:28.133 --> 31:30.033
May, pick a slice, any slice.

31:30.100 --> 31:31.567
I'll choose this one.

31:31.633 --> 31:33.000
Now you may change your mind if you wish.

31:33.567 --> 31:34.667
Okay.

31:34.967 --> 31:36.300
(LAUGHTER)

31:36.967 --> 31:38.667
Oh, good choice.
That's my favorite. Okay.

31:39.300 --> 31:43.233
By the way, this trick is not
gluten-free. I apologize. Okay.

31:44.167 --> 31:45.867
May, go ahead and memorize your slice.

31:46.467 --> 31:48.367
It's white bread, just like me.

31:48.600 --> 31:50.800
All right, go ahead.
Put it in the toaster for me.

31:51.167 --> 31:52.667
Get that baby fired up.

31:52.733 --> 31:54.600
Okay... (GASPS) and she cooks, too.

31:54.667 --> 31:56.333
Awesome. Okay.

31:56.933 --> 31:58.267
Ziploc bag right there.

31:58.333 --> 31:59.667
Inside of it, a deck of cards.

31:59.733 --> 32:01.933
People in the front, you might
see a familiar card here

32:02.000 --> 32:03.533
in the plastic of the bag.

32:03.600 --> 32:04.767
People in the back...

32:04.833 --> 32:06.700
Come early next time.

32:06.767 --> 32:07.833
Good, okay, great.

32:07.900 --> 32:10.233
I'm gonna shuffle.
We'll let the lovely May select a card.

32:10.300 --> 32:12.600
May, reach in there with your left hand,
just take out one card.

32:12.667 --> 32:14.400
Just take one, don't be greedy.
Don't show me.

32:14.467 --> 32:16.667
Don't show the audience.
Whatever you do, do not show

32:16.733 --> 32:18.467
the psychic toaster.
Good.

32:19.000 --> 32:20.267
Have you memorized your card, May?

32:20.333 --> 32:21.500
-Yes.
-Good.

32:21.567 --> 32:25.400
I will now pass the thought
of the card through May's body.

32:27.067 --> 32:29.167
I know, you're thinking,
over my dead body.

32:30.433 --> 32:33.067
Actually, May, the thoughts will
travel using a kitchen fork

32:33.300 --> 32:36.633
because thoughts are electric,
so the fork is the conduit... (SIZZLES)

32:36.800 --> 32:37.967
Ho!

32:38.033 --> 32:39.367
(CHUCKLES)

32:40.533 --> 32:41.833
(BLOWS AIR) Yow.

32:42.333 --> 32:43.667
Your turn.

32:45.233 --> 32:47.633
All right, don't electrocute
yourself, just hold that.

32:48.067 --> 32:49.733
-Buzz!
-(CHUCKLES)

32:49.800 --> 32:52.033
Okay, I have some safety
equipment. One second.

32:53.633 --> 32:55.567
Watching you.
Easy with that fork.

32:55.633 --> 32:58.233
Okay, no need to tenderize
Mr. Magic, okay.

32:59.633 --> 33:00.867
I'll take the fork.

33:01.533 --> 33:04.600
Even as I speak, the toaster has begun
to singe an image into the bread.

33:04.667 --> 33:05.867
I'll need your hand.

33:05.933 --> 33:08.567
Perfect. Now, think of your card.
Stay in the show.

33:08.633 --> 33:10.700
Think of your card flowing
through your body.

33:10.900 --> 33:12.167
Here we go.

33:14.067 --> 33:17.700
Ah! Did you feel our thoughts
race into the toaster, May?

33:18.800 --> 33:20.000
-Yes.
-Remember who has the pointy fork.

33:20.067 --> 33:21.433
Yes, she said.

33:21.967 --> 33:24.767
Even as I speak, the toaster is
singing an image into the bread,

33:24.833 --> 33:26.967
and if there is an image
on this slice of bread

33:27.033 --> 33:30.700
that looks like the card that May
selected, will this be a good trick?

33:31.167 --> 33:32.333
ALL: Yes.

33:32.400 --> 33:34.367
It'd be a miracle.
Come on, people.

33:34.433 --> 33:37.567
Mind reading toaster not a tad
unusual to some of you.

33:37.733 --> 33:38.833
Okay.

33:38.900 --> 33:40.967
May, tell me,
take a little step forward, if you would.

33:41.033 --> 33:43.367
Tell me, what is the card
that you picked?

33:43.533 --> 33:45.933
-Tell me.
-Uh, two.

33:46.067 --> 33:47.667
Two, yes, two of diamonds, yes.

33:47.733 --> 33:51.233
Show them, show them right out
in front like, two of diamonds.

33:51.300 --> 33:54.100
Popping the bread out of the toaster.
Can you hold it up just like that?

33:54.467 --> 33:55.533
Yep, take a look.

33:56.733 --> 33:58.133
Can't buy a reaction like that.

33:58.200 --> 34:01.933
It's really a two and a diamond.
It is a psychic toaster.

34:02.300 --> 34:03.500
Wow.

34:03.767 --> 34:05.633
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

34:07.433 --> 34:08.933
Let's hear it for May.

34:09.933 --> 34:12.233
Bruce Gold, ladies and gentlemen,
Bruce Gold.

34:12.400 --> 34:13.933
-Bruce, that was great.
-Thank you, Jonathan.

34:14.000 --> 34:16.100
Very funny, and also a great trick.

34:16.167 --> 34:18.833
I have no idea how you did that,
of course.

34:19.067 --> 34:21.199
But what is that, you said this
was a genuine toaster.

34:21.266 --> 34:23.300
I've never seen a one-slice toaster.

34:23.367 --> 34:24.766
Was this really something
that was for sale?

34:24.833 --> 34:26.266
It's a real toaster

34:26.333 --> 34:28.467
made back in the forties.
Apartments were very tiny then.

34:28.533 --> 34:29.699
-Yeah.
-(LAUGHTER)

34:29.766 --> 34:32.867
It struck me though, it was
a great mix of the comedy and the magic,

34:32.933 --> 34:34.467
and that's very hard to bring together.

34:34.533 --> 34:36.933
So congratulations to Bruce
once again for pulling that off

34:37.067 --> 34:39.333
'cause it was so entertaining,

34:40.100 --> 34:41.833
but I think the fellows may have

34:41.900 --> 34:45.600
come to an agreement whether or
not they're right, you can say.

34:45.833 --> 34:47.167
Gentlemen?

34:47.233 --> 34:51.533
Well, you know, we're having
a great example here of comedy magic.

34:52.033 --> 34:56.000
And in comedy magic,
many times people forget to do

34:56.067 --> 34:58.067
the comedy and the magic.

34:58.367 --> 35:00.733
And it's wonderful to see
somebody do both.

35:01.067 --> 35:04.400
We're thrilled to pieces
to see a toaster on stage.

35:06.067 --> 35:08.733
There's a great deal of
confidence with that.

35:08.800 --> 35:10.433
The trick is a really, really good trick.

35:10.500 --> 35:12.033
-Thank you.
-There's two pieces of information,

35:12.100 --> 35:15.033
which is getting the image
onto the toaster,

35:15.533 --> 35:19.500
and then there is you could
either worry about that as

35:19.700 --> 35:23.067
how do you have 52 possible images
that could be burned onto a toaster.

35:23.267 --> 35:25.200
Or there's another way to do that,
of course.

35:25.667 --> 35:30.867
And it turns out that my daughter,
when she was maybe three years old,

35:31.067 --> 35:35.200
she used a little plastic bag so
that there could be a random card

35:35.267 --> 35:37.800
picked out of that, and did a wonderful,

35:37.867 --> 35:42.233
wonderful job with that,
and as much as I love my daughter,

35:42.400 --> 35:44.500
and as cute as she was
on The View,

35:44.700 --> 35:46.700
you did a much
better job with that trick.

35:46.900 --> 35:48.667
You didn't fool us, but you killed us.

35:48.733 --> 35:50.033
Thank you so much.

35:50.100 --> 35:51.600
Wow.
Thank you.

35:51.667 --> 35:53.467
So, Bruce, just to confirm...

35:53.533 --> 35:54.667
Yes.

35:55.533 --> 35:57.500
They nailed you.
They know how you did it.

35:57.567 --> 35:59.267
You think they're in the right area there?

35:59.333 --> 36:01.533
They are in the right neighborhood.

36:01.600 --> 36:02.833
I would say yes.

36:02.900 --> 36:04.800
Bruce, well, you didn't fool
them, but you gave us all

36:04.867 --> 36:06.300
a great show, didn't he,
ladies and gentlemen?

36:06.933 --> 36:08.867
Bruce Gold, ladies and gentlemen.
Thank you so much.

36:08.933 --> 36:10.600
That was fabulous.

36:10.833 --> 36:12.367
Mr. Bruce Gold.

36:15.533 --> 36:17.533
Now these guys have been
performing magic together

36:17.633 --> 36:19.267
for over four decades,

36:19.333 --> 36:22.033
which makes this next trick the second
oldest one in the books.

36:22.200 --> 36:24.933
The first oldest is pretending
to yawn so you can put your arm

36:25.000 --> 36:26.067
around a lady's shoulders.

36:26.133 --> 36:27.467
That's an oldie, but a goodie,
but here they are,

36:27.533 --> 36:30.367
ladies and gentlemen,
the phenomenal Penn and Teller.

36:30.500 --> 36:32.600
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

36:32.833 --> 36:34.233
(JAZZ MUSIC)

36:48.333 --> 36:50.300
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

36:55.367 --> 36:58.100
This is not intended to
glorify smoking.

36:58.167 --> 37:01.167
That said... Looks simple, doesn't it?

37:02.400 --> 37:05.133
But when you're dealing with
a master of sleight of hand

37:05.200 --> 37:06.867
like my partner, Teller,

37:06.933 --> 37:11.500
even the simplest activity
may be a complex deception.

37:13.033 --> 37:16.100
Let's watch that routine again.

37:16.800 --> 37:19.467
Is he really crushing out his cigarette?

37:19.867 --> 37:22.033
Is he really adjusting his hat?

37:22.567 --> 37:24.800
Is he really pulling out
a fresh cigarette?

37:25.067 --> 37:28.033
Is he really bothered by that
itch in his left eye?

37:28.300 --> 37:32.600
Is he really just lighting a cigarette?

37:37.767 --> 37:40.967
To understand the complexity
of Teller's life,

37:41.833 --> 37:46.633
you need to know the seven
basic principles of magic.

37:48.100 --> 37:49.500
(APPLAUSE)

37:49.667 --> 37:51.667
One, palm.

37:52.233 --> 37:56.333
To hold an object in an apparently
empty hand.

37:57.167 --> 37:58.633
Two, ditch.

37:58.767 --> 38:01.667
To secretly dispose of an unneeded object.

38:02.733 --> 38:04.267
Three, steal.

38:04.333 --> 38:05.900
The opposite of ditch.

38:05.967 --> 38:08.467
To secretly obtain a needed object.

38:09.233 --> 38:10.900
Four, load.

38:11.167 --> 38:14.000
To secretly move the needed object to...

38:14.767 --> 38:16.067
Where it's needed.

38:16.833 --> 38:19.033
Five, simulation.

38:19.333 --> 38:23.067
To give the impression
that something that hasn't happened has.

38:24.100 --> 38:25.767
Six, misdirection.

38:25.933 --> 38:28.067
To lead attention away
from the secret move.

38:28.533 --> 38:30.200
And seven, switch.

38:30.400 --> 38:33.967
To secretly exchange
one object for another.

38:34.100 --> 38:36.200
(CHEERS AND APPLAUSE)

38:39.767 --> 38:42.433
Teller needs nothing but a pencil,

38:43.300 --> 38:47.167
one lit cigarette,
and a flashlight.

38:48.067 --> 38:50.900
Let's watch that original
routine again.

